                children: "Emergent behavior, as Bert just mentioned, is behavior that emerges unexpectedly and spontaneously as a result of interactions between different components, such as people, animals, things or systems. In this case, this happens when you add different parts to a cell, which then interact with each other, which can lead to unexpected behavior. So by isolating you ultimately get a bit more focus on specifically all the properties of one particular protein complex or a particular system that you would otherwise indeed lose. So ultimately you do provide much more understanding of how certain processes work and what side processes might also come with it. Have you ever seen something really new come out of that that also explains something else? So by examining a very isolated system, you see that it not only does A, but also B and C or thus has other properties as well and that then explains that a living system can show such a thing."
