                className: "english",
                children: "Yes, I already have several examples. Are you familiar with the concept of bistability, tipping points? Let's say, if you look at the climate now, it's very often said that we try to prevent the warming of the earth from being more than one and a half or two degrees, because above that we might reach a tipping point where it's actually, where it's very difficult to find a way back. In biological systems you also very often see such tipping points, where a cell, when it does something, can reach a point somewhere where it can go one way, in terms of its behavior, properties. And if the conditions are slightly different, then it goes completely the other way. And those kinds of tipping points in biology, very often we don't understand them precisely, but they can also have to do, and that's what we've seen, with an enzyme that has cooperative properties. And you've probably heard of positive and negative cooperativity in enzyme reactions. And positive cooperativity actually means that the activity of an enzyme changes very strongly over a very small concentration range. And so normally you know the hyperbolic dependencies. Well, then things change relatively slowly. If you have strong cooperativity, then over a very small concentration range a very large change in activity can already occur. And, well, how did we see that? We were working on finishing a manuscript and what we often do then, we've done all the experiments, but then we want to repeat everything three times, so that we have an N of 3 and then we can also calculate averages and standard deviations and that kind of thing. What we saw was that under many conditions the data were beautifully reproducible, but under one condition there were always points that didn't fit. So let's say the standard deviations were very small for most data, but very large. Well, that turned out to be traceable to the fact that we were working in that cell, in a concentration regime that sits exactly on the tipping point for the activity of that enzyme. If you were slightly below that, then the enzyme in that reaction was hardly active. If you were slightly above it, it was maximally active. The nice thing about that is that we see it, we can now understand it in the mathematical model, but we can also build on it further and understand, well what can such bistabilities mean in complex systems. Well, I think that will ultimately also be relevant for real living systems, for real biology. Only we have then hopefully described it a bit more precisely."
