            className: "line speaker2",
            children: [e.jsx("span", {
                className: "speaker",
                children: "Guest:"
            }), e.jsx("span", {
                className: "english",
                children: "Yes, well yes, I think if you look at what has happened in the past decades, there's naturally already a shift taking place. Look, in the Netherlands it's sensitive for certain political parties and certain religious groups to work on embryos. At the same time, the majority of the population, I think, believes that should be possible. Because if you look politically at how political parties stand on this, if you had asked those same questions in the fifties, in the seventies the answer would probably have been different. Mid-seventies actually, early seventies is when recombinant DNA technology was developed. Well there in the beginning it was also said maybe we should stop now, embargo, to see yes what can we do and how dangerous is it and let's just pause for a moment. All kinds of regulations came out of that about what should and shouldn't be able to be done. And ultimately it came out of that that it has all kinds of desired advantages to do that. That conclusion was drawn somewhat earlier in the United States than in Europe. But well, at this moment I think most people believe that this kind of research should be able to be done. Yes, so that shifting regarding these kinds of points, you always see that I think. And how that will go now with genetic research on embryos remains to be seen, but I think it will continue."
            })]
