                className: "english",
                children: "In terms of skills, I think I've applied most of it in my master's, from really the practical laboratory work. Writing down all the things you do in a logbook with pictures. It's funny, I'm now working on software development of a logbook tool. This is for a technical company, but it has basically exactly the same purpose as our logbook that we had in the laboratory. You have to be able to demonstrate afterwards what you did, how you did it, when you did it, why you thought something worked or didn't work. And yes, that collaboration too, that also comes back now in the product we're developing. Presenting something on a poster, yes, that's always useful to do of course. I still have to do that sometimes within my software projects. And experimenting. Even as a software developer, it's useful to know that what you're doing isn't going to work or probably isn't going to work, but you put two or three hours of time for it in your schedule, then you just try it and see where you end up. If you don't end up where you actually wanted to be, you might come to another useful point or you can try again later in a different way."
