                className: "english",
                children: "Yes, that's really a shortcut indeed, but it does play a role partly. In some countries it's quite easy for patients to get antibiotics and thus also use them for a cough, which could just as well be caused by a virus, so it makes no sense at all. So in the Netherlands we have that reasonably under control, but still, the problem really plays here too. So we wanted to tackle that problem mainly from the diagnostics angle, like you're actually doing now in your theme. Yes, just faster, easier, cheaper diagnostics, so that we at least always test and identify what kind of infection is actually at play. And yes, I think in that period there was also attention for this now and then I think it maybe started a bit more publicly and there was also once a discussion about it in the Second Chamber in that period around the use of bacteriophages. The principle is already quite old, especially in Russia and Georgia it's still done a lot now. But in Western medicine they kind of moved away from that at some point when antibiotics became big. While bacteriophages are actually a nice natural control agent. So those are viruses for bacteria. And the nice thing about that is that they co-evolve with bacteria. So bacteria can become resistant, certainly against bacteriophages, but those bacteriophages also adapt again to... So there's a kind of co-evolution going on. Yes, I think I once saw something on TV or so, and Duchamp-Alpenet in Belgium also came up there. So yes, that was just a very clear connection with that problem we had in our heads. But then something more on therapy of course. And then we also thought like yes, I think, researched in the literature, not much has been done yet with bacteriophages and their diagnostic application. So we searched into that and that's how it came together in that way. That was discussed with those people in Brussels and brainstormed further about it with our professors here too. And so we gradually formed the project towards using bacteriophages to specifically recognize bacteria actually. And then detect bacteriophage DNA with a sensor for DNA specifically. Well, that's how CRISPR-Cas also came into the picture. And that's what ultimately became the sensor, the solution. And later the whole part with bacteriophages maybe wasn't the most convenient after all. In any case that turned out in the iGEM project, and we mainly focused on that sensor actually for DNA, I could directly register the bacterial DNA of course. That actually works quite well. We struggled with that the whole time. Because the basis is a Cas9 protein. And the nice thing about that protein is that you can make it bind very specifically to a certain sequence of DNA. DNA consists of multiple letters actually, a certain sequence. And you can program that Cas9 protein with an RNA molecule that then fits exactly on that DNA. And so you can make it bind. And that binding in our sensor then causes a luciferase to be activated. And that's an enzyme that gives light. So in that way, when we see blue light, then we know it has bound to DNA. So that DNA is present among the bacteria."
