                className: "english",
                children: "HARM just mentioned the term codon optimization. Codon optimization is a technique used in protein production. It means that you adjust the genetic code of the DNA so that it better matches the preferences of the organism where you want it to work. In a cell, DNA is used as a recipe to make proteins. The DNA contains codons that can be translated by the cell into a specific building block for a protein, an amino acid. Although different codons can mean the same amino acid, some organisms prefer certain codons much more than others for a particular amino acid. By following this preference, the same translation process to a protein and thus the production of that protein can be made much more efficient. Do you know how that worked exactly? Or did you just at some point reverse it, okay, let's do it without optimization and then you noticed."
