                className: "english",
                children: "Hemophilia is thus a disease that occurs mainly in men. This is because factor 8 and 9 are described on the X chromosome. Women have two X chromosomes and thus double the chance of making the right factor 8 and 9, but men have an X and a Y chromosome. If the X chromosome they get from their parents is not functional for the clotting factors, then a man automatically also has hemophilia. In women it can also occur, even though it is much rarer. That's due to a process called lyonization. A woman namely has 2 X chromosomes, but the body has no use for making everything double. And therefore it rolls a random dice in every cell to turn off 1 of the 2 X genes, or to lyonize. So it can be that a girl gets a healthy X from her father and a hemophilia X chromosome from her mother. If you then have a lot of bad luck with throwing this dice, as it were, it can be that still many cells turn off the good X chromosome, so you can still get hemophilia complaints. So the girl still has hemophilia, even though she does have a correct gene in her cells."
