                className: "english",
                children: "Yes, so we certainly don't expect that either. So with us the main problem we have now, there are several, but the biggest underlying problem is that we can't measure sensitively enough yet. So the sensor changes color, that's nice, but ultimately there must of course be a correlation with how much color change there is, with what concentration of bile acid you have. And that's currently quite difficult to measure, especially in the concentrations we want to be able to measure to establish the disease picture. And besides, in the assay, we dissolve the bile acids in ethanol. That's because the bile acids don't dissolve very easily in water. The only problem we have with that now, is that the ethanol damages the protein a bit. So we see a very big color difference. Only that's unfortunately not caused by the bile acids, but just because the protein breaks down."
