                className: "english",
                children: "Later thought, oh... Yes, not really very bad. I think I had those lab experiences earlier in my education. Once during my BEP I had to use a small tabletop centrifuge. And it had a kind of lid that you have to put on it, a metal lid. And I had forgotten that. And it was a step where the lids weren't closed on the tubes you used. They were open. So I turned on that centrifuge. And because both the metal lid wasn't on top, and those tubes were all open. Yes, a lot of force comes on in such a centrifuge. It goes at 13,000 rpm or something. Yes, all those lids were torn off in the centrifuge, which made the thing start making a lot of noise and start rattling, so I quickly pressed stop. Well, as a bachelor student you're immediately in panic like shit, what did I do? Well, ultimately nothing was wrong. Then Harm I think, solved that for me. He just took that thing out and helped fish all those things out. Well, you never forget that. But yes, then you have within your first things, yes I can also remember from my first research, then you forget a step and then your research doesn't work. Then your cloning doesn't work or your cell doesn't grow or something like that. Yes, half of that time it just comes because I made cell errors. Yes, I notice that I really haven't made those errors now actually."
